T1  - Grades of Membership and Legitimacy Spillovers: Foreign Banks in Shanghai, 1847–1935
AU  - Kuilman, Jeroen G.
AU  - Li, Jiatao
Y1  - 2009/04/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2009.37308018
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2009.37308018
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 229
EP  - 245
VL  - 52
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this study, we formulated and tested a theory about how heterogeneity among subpopulations affects the degree to which organizations in these subpopulations contribute to and benefit from the overall population's legitimacy. Historical data on banking in Shanghai were used. Firms in subpopulations with a higher ?grade of membership? were found to contribute strongly to the legitimacy of the general population; firms in subpopulations with a lower grade of membership benefited most from legitimacy spillovers. The concepts of ?fuzzy density,? ?contrast,? and public acceptance were applied to measuring legitimacy.
AB  - In this study, we formulated and tested a theory about how heterogeneity among subpopulations affects the degree to which organizations in these subpopulations contribute to and benefit from the overall population's legitimacy. Historical data on banking in Shanghai were used. Firms in subpopulations with a higher ?grade of membership? were found to contribute strongly to the legitimacy of the general population; firms in subpopulations with a lower grade of membership benefited most from legitimacy spillovers. The concepts of ?fuzzy density,? ?contrast,? and public acceptance were applied to measuring legitimacy.
